-- U.S. Gulf Coast Sour Crudes Gain, Sweet Oils Slip Against WTI
-- B y   A a r o n   C l a r k
-- 2012-04-23T22:06:40Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2012-04-23/u-s-gulf-coast-sour-crudes-gain-sweet-oils-slip-against-wti.html
U.S. Gulf Coast sour crudes
strengthened and sweeter oils weakened against the benchmark
West Texas Intermediate.  Mars Blend added 35 cents against WTI to a premium of
$11.50. Poseidon’s premium increased 40 cents to $10.40, while
Southern Green Canyon’s added 25 cents to $10.25. The three
grades are used in the Argus Sour Crude Index.  Thunder Horse ,
which has lower sulfur content than the other three grades, a
lost 5 cents to $14.20 a barrel over WTI.  Sweet oils weakened against the benchmark. Light Louisiana
Sweet’s premium to WTI lost 15 cents to $17.60 a barrel at 4:30
p.m. New York time, according to data compiled by Bloomberg.
Heavy Louisiana Sweet weakened 25 cents to a premium of $17 a
barrel.  Brent crude’s premium over WTI, based on June futures
prices, widened 72 cents to $15.60 a barrel in New York. When
Brent increases versus WTI, it typically strengthens the value
of low-sulfur U.S. grades that compete with West African oil
priced against the European benchmark.  Western Canada Select’s discount to WTI widened 40 cents to
$17 a barrel. Syncrude’s discount widened 50 cents to $1.50 and
Bakken oil’s discount was unchanged at $6.50.  To contact the reporter on this story:
